definition.value: An oxodocosahexaenoate that is the conjugate base of (4Z,7Z,10Z,13Z,15E,19Z)-17-oxodocosahexaenoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
An aryl sulfate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the sulfo group of any phenyl sulfate; major species at pH 7.3.

A racemate comprising equimolar amounts of (R)- and (S)-tefuryltrione. An inhibitor of 4-hydroxyphenyl-pyruvate dioxygenase, it is used as a herbicide for the treatment of annual and perennial weeds in rice paddies.

A beta-triketone that is 2-benzoylcyclohexane-1,3-dione in which the benzoyl group is substituted at positions 2, 3, and 4 by chlorine, (tetrahydrofuran-2-ylmethoxy)methyl, and methylsulfonyl groups, respectively.
A 2-{2-chloro-4-(methylsulfonyl)-3-[(tetrahydrofuran-2-ylmethoxy)methyl]benzoyl}cyclohexane-1,3-dione that has R configuration.
A 2-{2-chloro-4-(methylsulfonyl)-3-[(tetrahydrofuran-2-ylmethoxy)methyl]benzoyl}cyclohexane-1,3-dione that has S configuration.
A compound that contains three ketone functionalities.
A triketone in which the each ketone functionality is located beta- to the other two.
A carboxamide resulting from the formal condensation of a carboxylic acid with ammonia; formula RC(=O)NH2.
A carboxamide resulting from the formal condensation of a carboxylic acid with a primary amine; formula RC(=O)NHR(1).
A carboxamide resulting from the formal condensation of a carboxylic acid with a secondary amine; formula RC(=O)NHR(1)R(2).
Any beta-D-galactoside derived from alpha-L-fucosyl-(1->2)-beta-D-galactose.
Any beta-D-galactoside derived from alpha-D-galactosyl-(1->3)-[alpha-L-fucosyl-(1->2)]-beta-D-galactose.
An anthracyline cation that is the conjugate acid of 13-deoxycarminomycin, obtained by protonation of the amino group. Major microspecies at pH 7.3
An anthracyline cation that is the conjugate acid of (13R)-13-dihydrocarminomycin, obtained by protonation of the amino group. Major microspecies at pH 7.3
Any hydroxyflavanone having a hydroxy substituent located at position 4'.
Any methoxyflavanone having a methoxy substituent located at position 4'.
A docosanoid anion that is the conjugate base of (7Z,10Z,13Z,15E,19Z)-17-oxodocosapentaenoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A polyanionic polymer obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy groups of glucuronoxylan D-glucuronate. Major microspecies at pH 7.3
A polyanionic polymer obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy groups of glucuronoxylan 4-O-methyl-D-glucuronate. Major microspecies at pH 7.3
An icosanoid anion that is the conjugate base of (6E,8Z,11Z,14Z,17Z)-5-oxoicosapentaenoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
Any polyunsaturated fatty acid carrying one or more hydroxy substituents.
A docosanoid anion that is the conjugate base of 17R,(16)-epoxy-(4Z,7Z,10Z,13Z,19Z)-docosahexa-4,7,10,13,15,19-enoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
An amino acid zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group of any substituted beta-amino acid; major species at pH 7.3.
A docosanoid anion that is the conjugate base of 22-hydroxyprotectin D1, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A docosanoid anion that is the conjugate base of (7S,17S)-bis(hydroperoxy)-(4Z,8E,10Z,13Z,15E,19Z)-docosahexaenoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A dihydroxydocosahexaenoate that is the conjugate base of (7S,14S)-dihydroxy-(4Z,8E,10E,12Z,16Z,19Z)-docosahexaenoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
Any methoxyflavanone having a methoxy substituent located at position 3'.
A dihydroxydocosahexaenoate that is the conjugate base of resolvin D5, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
Any methoxyisoflavone that has a methoxy group at the 7-position of the isoflavone moiety.
An N(4)-glycosylated L-asparagine residue that is a representation of high mannose glucans.
An organophosphate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of any monosaccharide 1-phosphate.This compound class represents generic and unspecified sugar 1-phosphates.
A nucleotide-sugar oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of any UDP-monosaccharide. This compound class represents generic and unspecified UDP-sugars.
An anionic amino-acid residue residue that is a representation of high mannose glucans.
An N(4)-glycosylated L-asparagine residue that is a representation of high mannose glucans, but it is not known exactly which high mannose glucan is modified, (see EC 2.7.8.17 and EC 3.1.4.45)

An inositol phosphate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of all but one of the phosphate and diphosphate OH groups of 3,5-bis(diphospho)-1D-myo-inositol 1,2,4,6-tetrakisphosphate. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
A hydroxydocosahexaenoate that is the conjugate base of (4Z,8E,10Z,13Z,16Z,19Z)-7-hydroxydocosahexaenoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
An inositol phosphate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate OH groups of 3-diphospho-1D-myo-inositol 1,2,4,5,6-pentakisphosphate. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3.
A hydroxydocosahexaenoate that is the conjugate base of (8E,10Z,13Z,16Z,19Z)-docosapentaenoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
